title: For Sale:  Chinese Milled Receiver Ak-47 Polytech 386 stamp
postcontent:
Chinese Milled Receiver Ak-47 Polytech 386 stamp

Excellent condition ... Couldn't have been shot much if ever!

General Specifications
Caliber:7.62x39mm
Overall length 35.1 inches
Barrel length 16.34 inches
Weight with empty magazine 8 lbs 4 ounces

All MAK-90 rifles have stamped sheet metal receivers except a small lot of rifles imported (by China Jing An - C.J.A.) that had receivers milled from a solid block of material. These receivers were manufactured by Chinese State Factory 386. They were all designed for the typical AK 7.62x39 ammo. The stamped and milled receivers can be easily distinguished from one another because the stamped receiver has rivets holding it together and the milled receiver has only one rivet at the front of the receiver, and is obviously milled instead of dimpled.

The letters/numbers MAK-90 stand for Modified AK-1990. The MAK-90 is a Chinese factory built AK model exported to the USA from China from 1990 through 1994 by Norinco. Following the import ban in 1989, the Chinese developed an AK which met the "sporting purposes" clause. (The earlier AKs were banned because of their "evil" features: pistol grips, folding stocks, threaded muzzles and bayonets.) The new model was basically an AK with a wood thumb-hole stock and no bayonet lug.

The model name was ground off (or lined through) and the new model name MAK-90 was stamped. They were named "Sporter," to make them seem more like hunting rifles.

The stamp 386 on receiver and butt stock is the factory stamp for Polytech and this rifle includes the original sling and 1 magazine.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Sky CPX-1
postcontent: The CPX-1 is the first firearm offered by Skyy Industries. While the gun may bear some resemblance to other guns on the market, Skyy is plowing a lot of new ground with this gun.The CPX-1 is only offered in 9mm. The CPX-1 is very compact and nearly identical in size to a Kel-Tec P-11. This is a good size for a concealed carry piece—large enough to shoot well, but small enough to carry easily. The gun has a concealed hammer, as opposed to the striker-type action seen in many modern DAO guns. The magazines hold 9 rounds, so with one in the chamber, you can carry a full complement of 10 rounds.
